# KUKA KRL Conventions

When editing `.src`, `.dat`, or `.sub` files, follow these conventions. They are enforced by the QA agent and the `safety_lint` MCP server.

## Program Structure

- Every main `DEF ... END` program starts with an `INI` block (macro from `$config.dat`) that initializes `$BASE`, `$TOOL`, `$VEL`, `$ACC`, and interrupts.
- Subprograms are declared `GLOBAL DEF <name>(...)` in their own `.src` files; reusable data goes in `.dat` files.
- `GLOBAL DEFDAT` files for shared, persistent variables; local `DEFDAT` for program-private data.
- One concept per file; long programs get decomposed into subprograms.

## Motion

- Set `$TOOL`, `$BASE`, `$IPO_MODE` explicitly before the first motion command — never rely on inherited state.
- Set `$VEL.CP` (Cartesian path velocity), `$VEL_AXIS[]` (axis velocity percentage), and `$ACC.CP` explicitly before motion blocks.
- SPLINE blocks require `BAS(#INITMOV, 0)` (or equivalent) before use; otherwise path initialization is undefined.
- Prefer PTP for point-to-point, LIN for linear, SPLINE for complex continuous paths. `CIRC` for arcs only.
- Approach/retract offsets via `$TOOL` or explicit `FRAME` arithmetic — not hard-coded Cartesian literals in `LIN` commands.

## Variables and I/O

- Every `DECL` has a descriptive comment: `DECL INT gripper_state ; 0=open 1=closed 2=fault`.
- Signal I/O accesses use named aliases from `$config.dat` (`SIGNAL gripper_cmd $OUT[12]`), never raw `$OUT[12]` in program text.
- No hard-coded numeric literals where a named configuration constant applies.

## Interrupts and Safety

- `INTERRUPT DECL <prio> WHEN <cond> DO <handler>()` for safety-relevant events (E-stop, guard open, part present loss), declared **before first motion**.
- Interrupt priorities follow house convention (see `kuka_dataset/normalized/safety/` once populated).
- Error recovery logic in dedicated subprograms, not inline.

## Comments and Documentation

- File header: purpose, author, revision date, dependencies.
- Section headers separate logical phases: `; === PICK ===`, `; === PLACE ===`.
- Comment intent, not mechanics. Do not comment "increment counter"; comment why.

